15","1246":"1246","about 1215":"about 1215","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1210":"about 1210","1180":"1180","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ab","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  African/Muslim Amadou, Ousmane, Demba, Mamadou, Daouda, Ibrahima, Mohamed, Thierno, Abdoul, Abdoulaye, Abou, Aissatou, Fatime, Fatou, Mame, Moussa, Oumar, Yassin.  Vietnamese Dung, Thai Van, Tho, Thuy, Toan, Tong Van, Tran.","West African (mainly Senegal and Mauritania): Fulani name, from the Mandinka adjective <i>ba(a)</i> ‘big, great’. Compare   Bah   1, see also   Balde   1.","Muslim: abstracted as a surname from <i>bā</i>, a dialect form of Arabic <i>Abu</i> ‘father’, used in compound surnames such as <i>Bā Wazīr</i> and <i>Bā Ṭarafi</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Balde","meanings":["West African (mainly Senegal and Mauritania): Fulani name, regarded as an equivalent (variant) of   Ba   1.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>bald</i> ‘bold, quick’ (see   Bald  ).","Catalan (<b>Baldé</b>): possibly from an old personal name of ancient Germanic origin (see 2 above)."]},{"name":"Bah","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  African/Muslim Mamadou, Thierno, Amadou, Boubacar, Fatmata, Fatoumata, Mariama, Oumou, Umaru, Aboubacar, Aissatou, Alieu, Mohamed, Abdulai, Ibrahima, Abdul, Abdoul, Ibrahim, Abou, Abu, Abubakar, Ali, Hassane, Mahmoud.","West African (mainly Guinea, also common in the Gambia and Sierra Leone): variant of the Fulani name   Ba   1.","Slovenian: probably a nickname from a derivative of <i>bahati se</i> ‘to boast, to pride oneself’. Compare   Bach   7."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rhirid ab Madog II was born in 1175, his father, Madog II ab Iorwerth I, was 30 and his mother, Arddun verch Bradwen, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Nest ferch Gronwy. He died in 1246, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1175–1246":